ty of Birmingham]]'''\n| [[University of Birmingham]]\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| '''[[Loughborough University]]'''\n| [[Loughborough University]]\n|\n|-\n| 1994\n| '''[[Loughborough University]]'''\n| [[University of Surrey]]\n|\n|-\n| 1993\n| '''[[University of Birmingham]]'''\n| [[Bradford University]]\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| '''[[Loughborough University]]'''\n| [[Loughborough University]]\n|\n|-\n| 1991\n| '''[[University of Birmingham]]'''\n|[[UMIST]]\n|\n|-\n| 1990\n| '''[[University of Birmingham]]'''\n|[[University of Birmingham]]/[[Aston University]]\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| '''[[University of Birmingham]]'''\n|[[University of Nottingham]]\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| '''[[Loughborough University]]'''\n|[[Teesside Polytechnic]]\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| '''[[University of Birmingham]]'''\n|[[Newcastle University|University of Newcastle]]\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| '''[[University of Nottingham]]'''\n|[[London South Bank University|Southbank Polytechnic]]\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| '''Birmingham/Nottingham'''\n|[[Newcastle University]]\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Wins !! University !! Last Won\n|-\n| 16 || [[University of Birmingham|Birmingham]] || 2020\n|-\n| 7 || [[Loughborough University|Loughborough]] || 2004\n|-\n| 7 || [[Imperial College London]] || 2013\n|-\n| 2 || [[Manchester University|Manchester]] || 2009\n|-\n| 2 || [[University of Nottingham]] || 1986\n|-\n| 1 || [[University of Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle University]] || 1997\n|-\n| 1 || [[University of Strathclyde]] || 2014\n|-\n| 1 || [[University of Bath]] || 2000\n|-\n| 1 || [[University of Sheffield|Sheffield]] || 2003\n|-\n\n|}\n\n== Frank Morton Leeds 2018 ==\nIn 2018 Frank Morton was attended by around 2100 chemical engineers from 28 universities. 18 sporting events took place in various venues around Leeds. The careers fair and opening and closing ceremony were hosted in Leeds University Union. The evening entertainment saw carnival rides come to the union as well as the headline act- MistaJam.\n\n== Frank Morton Birmingham 2015 ==\nThe 2015 event was attended by around 2700 chemical engineering students from 29 UK and Irish universities. The event took take place at the [[Barclaycard Arena]], with students and companies to participating in 19 different sporting events located in venues around Birmingham.<ref name=TCEMarch2015>''The Chemical Engineer'' March 2015 p50 \"Morton in the Midlands\"</ref>\n\n==Frank Morton Newcastle 2013==\nThe event was hosted by [[Newcastle University]] on Tuesday 12 February and saw the scale of the event increase dramatically. The event took place in the [[Metro Radio Arena]], Newcastle, and was the first time the event has ever been held in a commercial venue. Over 2000 chemical engineering students from 24 UK and Irish universities participated in 15 different tournaments across the city.<ref name=TCE861>''The Chemical Engineer'' issue 861 (March 2013) pages 52-3</ref>\n\nWith 22 organisations financially supporting the event, \u00a360000 was raised. The event was partnered with [[ABB Group|ABB]] with sponsorship from [[GlaxoSmithKline|GSK]], [[Royal Navy]], [[Phillips 66]], [[Exxon Mobil]] and support from [[Bechtel]], [[Johnson Matthey]], [[Croda]], [[KBR (company)|KBR]], Davy Process Technology, Gradcracker, [[Valero Energy Corporation|Valero]] and [[Ineos]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Frank Morton Sports Day Newcastle 2013|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/410109499049464/|publisher=Frank Morton Newcastle|accessdate=2012-11-29}}</ref>\n\n==Previous Events==\nIn 2012, the event took place at Swansea University, 21 February 2012 and included a number of new events such as Laser Tag and Bowling. The 2012 event was won by Birmingham<ref name=waterfront>[http://www.waterfrontonline.co.uk/op/article/engineering-society-host-frank-morton-sports-day The Waterfront] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426001116/http://www.waterfrontonline.co.uk/op/article/engineering-society-host-frank-morton-sports-day |date=26 April 2012 }} 28 November 2011 \"Engineering Society to host Frank Morton Sports Day\"</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the event took place on 22 February at the University of Nottingham and was won by the University of Birmingham.<ref name=IChemEFMNott>[http://www.icheme.org/events/events/2011/frank%20morton%20sports%20day%202011.aspx www.icheme.org] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719014546/http://www.icheme.org/events/events/2011/frank%20morton%20sports%20day%202011.aspx |date=19 July 2011 }} Events: Frank Morton Sports Day 2011.</ref>\n\nIn 2010, the event was hosted, and won, by the University of Birmingham on 18 February.<ref name=TCE822>''The Chemical Engineer'' (December 2009-January 2010) page 52</ref>  It involved 1547 students from 20 universities.<ref name=TCE825>''The Chemical Engineer'' issue 825 (March 2010) page 60</ref>  The [[Asia-Pacific]] Frank Morton Sports Day in October 2010 was hosted by the Universiti Technologi Mara, Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.<ref name=TCE825/>\n\nIn 2009, Frank Morton Sports Day was held in Singapore as well as the UK for the first time.<ref name=TCE814/> In the UK, [[Newcastle University]] hosted the event.<ref name=ncl>[http://www.ncl.ac.uk/ceam/assets/documents/FrankMortonSportsDay2009.pdf Newcastle University] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306015706/http://www.ncl.ac.uk/ceam/assets/documents/FrankMortonSportsDay2009.pdf |date=6 March 2012 }} Frank Morton 2009</ref>  Overall winners were the University of Manchester, with Strathclyde second and Birmingham Third.<ref name=TCE814/><ref name=YouTubeFM>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gKc0yWplbdI www.youtube.com] Frank Morton 2009 awards ceremony</ref> The [[National University of Singapore]] hosted the Singapore event on 21 February 2009.  Overall winners were [[Universiti Teknologi MARA]] with [[University of Nottingham Malaysia Campus|University of Nottingham (Malaysia)]] second and National University of Singapore third.<ref name=TCE814/>\n\nIn 2008 the event took place on 19 February at the [[University of Leeds]].  1300 students from 17 universities and several company teams took part.  [[Imperial College London]] successfully defended their title as overall winners, with [[Birmingham University]] second and [[Strathclyde University]] third.  The champion company team was that from [[Bechtel]].<ref name=TCE802/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Student sport in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "WOSlinker", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix bold", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Morton_Sports_Day"}
{"title_page": "2008 Republican Party presidential primaries", "text_new": "{{see also|2008 Democratic Party presidential primaries}}\n{{2008 Republican Party presidential primaries|[[File:DSC 0031 (2855532414).jpgthumbDSC 0031 (2855532414)]]=}}\n{{US 2008 presidential elections series}}\nThe '''2008 Republican presidential primaries''' were the selection process by which voters of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] chose its nominee for [[President of the United States]] in the [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 U.S. presidential election]]. [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[John McCain]] of [[Arizona]] was selected as the nominee through a series of [[primary election]]s and [[caucus]]es culminating in the [[2008 Republican National Convention]] held from Monday, September 1, through Thursday, September 4, 2008, in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|St. Paul]], [[Minnesota]].  President George W. Bush was ineligible to be elected to a third term due to the term limits established by the 22nd Amendment.\n\nIn a crowded primary of several prominent Republicans eyeing the nomination, former New York City mayor [[Rudy Giuliani]] was the early frontrunner.<ref>Cohen et al., \"The Party Decides: Presidential Nominations Before and After Reform,\" Chicago: 2008, p 338.</ref> However, former Arkansas Governor [[Mike Huckabee]] won the Iowa Caucuses as he gained momentum just two months prior to the primary. Moderate U.S. Senator and former presidential candidate [[John McCain]] won the New Hampshire and Florida primaries. After failing to win in Florida, Giuliani ended his campaign.\n\nMcCain ultimately won the nomination after winning most of the primaries on [[Super Tuesday, 2008|Super Tuesday]]. \n\n==Candidates==\n{{main|Republican Party presidential candidates, 2008}}\n<!--\nCandidates:\n************************************************************************************** \n* This is a HISTORICAL article, NOT a running tally. DO NOT REMOVE PAST CANDIDATES.  *\n**************************************************************************************\n\n-->\n'''Notes for the following table:''' Delegate counts is the final estimated delegate count.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2008/primaries/results/scorecard/#val=R2 |title=Final GOP delegate count. Last Updated- August 28, 2008 |publisher=Cnn.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-09}}</ref>\n\n===Nominee===\nThe vast majority of primaries were of the \"winner-take-all\" variety, and convention rules meant that no one with less than five states in their \"pockets\" would be allowed to have their names placed in nomination. This guaranteed that the primary season would be very short. McCain won New Hampshire, South Carolina and Florida and thus became unstoppable. Huckabee nearly won Missouri but he failed, ending the race. Candidates are listed by delegate counts.\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=2 | Candidate \n! Most recent office \n! Home state \n! Estimated delegate count (RCP) \n! Candidacy \n! Delegations with plurality\n|- style=\"background:#e3f9d9;\"\n|[[Image:John McCain official portrait 2009.jpg|130px]]<br />'''<span style=\"display:none\">McCain, John</span><big>[[John McCain]]</big>'''\n| style=\"background:#00C000;\" |\n| '''[[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] from [[Arizona]]'''<br>(1987\u20132018)\n| [[File:Flag map of Arizona.svg|50px]]<br>[[Arizona]]\n| '''1,575'''<br><small>72.5%</small><br><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2008/primaries/results/scorecard/#val=R | work=CNN | title=Election Center 2008: Delegate Scorecard - Elections & Politics news from CNN.com | accessdate=May 22, 2010}}</ref>\n| '''Secured nomination:<br>March 4, 2008'''<br>[[John McCain 2008 presidential campaign|<small>(Campaign)</small>]]\n| '''31'''<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;[[New Hampshire Republican primary, 2008|NH]], [[South Carolina Republican primary, 2008|SC]], [[Florida Republican primary, 2008|FL]], [[New York Republican primary, 2008|NY]], [[California Republican primary, 2008|CA]], [[Illinois Republican primary, 2008|IL]], [[Missouri Republican primary, 2008|MO]], [[Oklahoma Republican primary, 2008|OK]], [[Connecticut Republican primary, 2008|CT]], [[Arizona Republican primary, 2008|AR]], [[New Jersey Republican primary, 2008|NJ]], [[Delaware Republican primary, 2008|DE]]&nbsp;&nbsp;<br> [[Washington Republican primary, 2008|WA]], [[Virginia Republican primary, 2008|VA]], [[Maryland Republican primary, 2008|MD]], [[Wisconsin Republican primary, 2008|WI]], [[Vermont Republican primary, 2008|VT]], [[Rhode Island Republican primary, 2008|RI]], [[Ohio Republican primary, 2008|OH]], [[Texas Republican primary, 2008|TX]], [[Mississippi Republican primary, 2008|MS]], [[Pennsylvania Republican primary, 2008|PA]], [[Indiana Republican primary, 2008|IN]]<br> [[North Carolina Republican primary, 2008|NC]], [[Nebraska Republican primary, 2008|NE]], [[Hawaii Republican caucuses, 2008|HI]], [[Kentucky Republican primary, 2008|KY]], [[Oregon Republican primary, 2008|OR]], [[Idaho Republican primary, 2008|ID]], [[South Dakota Republican primary, 2008|SD]], [[New Mexico Republican primary, 2008|NM]]<br>Non-states: [[District of Columbia Republican primary, 2008|DC]], [[Puerto Rico Republican caucuses, 2008|PR]], [[Northern Mariana Islands Republican caucuses, 2008|MP]], [[American Samoa Republican caucuses, 2008|AS]], [[United States Virgin Islands Republican caucuses, 2008|VI]], [[Guam Republican caucuses, 2008|GU]]</center>\n|-\n\n|[[Image:Huckabee-SF-CC-024.jpg|130px]]<br />'''<span style=\"display:none\">Huckabee, Mike</span><big>[[Mike Huckabee]]</big>''' \n| style=\"background:#ff2a7f;\" |\n| '''[[List of Governors of Arkansas|{{black|44th}}]]<br>[[Governor of Arkansas]]'''<br>(1996\u20132007)\n| [[File:Flag-map of Arkansas.svg|75px]]<br>[[Arkansas]] \n| '''278'''<br /><small>12.8%</small>\n| Withdrew:<br>March 4, 2008<br>[[Mike Huckabee presidential campaign, 2008|<small>(Campaign)</small>]]<br><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/03/04/march.4.contests/index.html |title= McCain clinches GOP nomination, CNN projects |accessdate=2008-03-04 |last= |first= |coauthors= |date= March 5, 2008|work= |publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n \n| '''8'''<br />[[Alabama Republican primary, 2008|AL]], [[Arkansas Republican primary, 2008|AR]], [[Georgia Republican primary, 2008|GA]], [[Iowa Republican caucuses, 2008|IA]], [[West Virginia Republican caucuses, 2008|WV]], [[Tennessee Republican primary, 2008|TN]]<br> [[Kansas Republican caucuses, 2008|KS]], [[Louisiana Republican caucuses, 2008|LA]]\n|-\n\n|[[File:Mitt Romney by Gage Skidmore 6.jpg|130px]]<br />'''<span style=\"display:none\">Romney, Mitt</span><big>[[Mitt Romney]]</big>''' \n| style=\"background:#ff6600;\" |\n| '''70th<br>[[Governor of Massachusetts]]'''<br>(2003\u20132007)\n| [[File:Flag-map of Massachusetts.svg|75px]]<br>[[Massachusetts]] \n| '''271'''<br /><small>12.5%</small>\n| Withdrew:<br> February 7, 2008<br>[[Mitt Romney presidential campaign, 2008|<small>(Campaign)</small>]]\n| '''11'''<br>[[Michigan Republican primary, 2008|MI]], [[Nevada Republican caucuses, 2008|NV]], [[Wyoming Republican caucuses, 2008|WY]], [[Maine Republican caucuses, 2008|ME]], [[Massachusetts Republican primary, 2008|MA]], [[Montana Republican caucuses, 2008|MT]]<br> [[Utah Republican primary, 2008|UT]], [[Minnesota Republican caucuses, 2008|MN]], [[Colorado Republican caucuses, 2008|CO]], [[North Dakota Republican caucuses, 2008|ND]], [[Alaska Republican caucuses, 2008|AK]]\n|-\n\n|[[Image:Ron Paul, official Congressional photo portrait, 2007.jpg|130px]]<br />'''<span style=\"display:none\">Paul, Ron</span><big>[[Ron Paul]]</big>''' \n| style=\"background:#ffd700;\" |\n| '''[[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]]<br> for [[Texas's 14th congressional district|Texas's 14th]]'''<br>(1997\u20132013)\n| [[File:Flag-map of Texas.svg|75px]]<br>[[Texas]] \n| '''35'''<br 