 2008|primary]]\n|27\n|10\n|3\n|17\n|'''57'''\n|\n|- align=center\u00a7\u00a7\u00a7\u00a7\n|[[North Carolina]]\n|[[North Carolina Republican primary, 2008|primary]]\n|39\n|10\n|3\n|17\n|'''69'''\n|\n|- align=center\n|May 13, 2008\n|[[Nebraska]]\n|[[Nebraska Republican primary, 2008|primary]]\n|9\n|10\n|3\n|11\n|'''33'''\n|- align=center\n|May 13, 2008\n|[[West Virginia]]\n|[[West Virginia Republican caucuses and primary, 2008|primary]]\n|9\n|10\n|3\n|8\n|'''12 of 30'''\n|- align=center\n|rowspan=2|May 20, 2008\n|[[Kentucky]]\n|[[Kentucky Republican primary, 2008|primary]]\n|18\n|10\n|3\n|14\n|'''45'''\n|\n|- align=center\n|[[Oregon]]\n|[[Oregon Republican primary, 2008|primary]]\n|15\n|10\n|3\n|2\n|'''30'''\n|\n|- align=center\n|May 27, 2008\n|[[Idaho]]\n|[[Idaho Republican primary, 2008|primary]]\n|6\n|10\n|3\n|13\n|'''32'''\n|\n|- align=center\n|rowspan=2|June 3, 2008\n|[[South Dakota]]\n|[[South Dakota Republican primary, 2008|primary]]\n|3\n|10\n|3\n|11\n|'''27'''\n|\n|- align=center\n|[[New Mexico]]\n|[[New Mexico Republican primary, 2008|primary]]\n|9\n|10\n|3\n|10\n|'''32'''\n|\n|- align=center\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''1,029'''\n|\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 2008]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{United States presidential election, 2008}}\n{{U.S. presidential primaries}}\n{{2008Repprimaries}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Republican Party (United States) Presidential Primaries, 2008}}\n[[Category:2008 United States Republican presidential primaries| ]]\n[[Category:Republican Party (United States) presidential primaries|2008]]\n", "text_old": "{{see also|2008 Democratic Party presidential primaries}}\n{{2008 Republican Party presidential primaries|[[File:DSC 0031 (2855532414).jpgthumbDSC 0031 (2855532414)]]=}}\n{{US 2008 presidential elections series}}\nThe '''2008 Republican presidential primaries''' were the selection process by which voters of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] chose its nominee for [[President of the United States]] in the [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 U.S. presidential election]]. [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[John McCain]] of [[Arizona]] was selected as the nominee through a series of [[primary election]]s and [[caucus]]es culminating in the [[2008 Republican National Convention]] held from Monday, September 1, through Thursday, September 4, 2008, in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|St. Paul]], [[Minnesota]].  President George W. Bush was ineligible to be elected to a third term due to the term limits established by the 22nd Amendment.\n\nIn a crowded primary of several prominent Republicans eyeing the nomination, former New York City mayor [[Rudy Giuliani]] was the early frontrunner.<ref>Cohen et al., \"The Party Decides: Presidential Nominations Before and After Reform,\" Chicago: 2008, p 338.</ref> However, former Arkansas Governor [[Mike Huckabee]] won the Iowa Caucuses as he gained momentum just two months prior to the primary. Moderate U.S. Senator and former presidential candidate [[John McCain]] won the New Hampshire and Florida primaries. After failing to win in Florida, Giuliani ended his campaign.\n\nMcCain ultimately won the nomination after winning most of the primaries on [[Super Tuesday, 2008|Super Tuesday]]. \n\n==Candidates==\n{{main|Republican Party presidential candidates, 2008}}\n<!--\nCandidates:\n************************************************************************************** \n* This is a HISTORICAL article, NOT a running tally. DO NOT REMOVE PAST CANDIDATES.  *\n**************************************************************************************\n\n-->\n'''Notes for the following table:''' Delegate counts is the final estimated delegate count.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2008/primaries/results/scorecard/#val=R2 |title=Final GOP delegate count. Last Updated- August 28, 2008 |publisher=Cnn.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-09}}</ref>\n\n===Nominee===\nThe vast majority of primaries were of the \"winner-take-all\" variety, and convention rules meant that no one with less than five states in their \"pockets\" would be allowed to have their names placed in nomination. This guaranteed that the primary season would be very short. McCain won New Hampshire, South Carolina and Florida and thus became unstoppable. Huckabee nearly won Missouri but he failed, ending the race. Candidates are listed by delegate counts.\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=2 | Candidate \n! Most recent office \n! Home state \n! Estimated delegate count (RCP) \n! Candidacy \n! Delegations with plurality\n|- style=\"background:#e3f9d9;\"\n|[[Image:John McCain official portrait 2009.jpg|130px]]<br />'''<span style=\"display:none\">McCain, John</span><big>[[John McCain]]</big>'''\n| style=\"background:#00C000;\" |\n| '''[[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] from [[Arizona]]'''<br>(1987\u20132018)\n| [[File:Flag map of Arizona.svg|50px]]<br>[[Arizona]]\n| '''1,575'''<br><small>72.5%</small><br><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2008/primaries/results/scorecard/#val=R | work=CNN | title=Election Center 2008: Delegate Scorecard - Elections & Politics news from CNN.com | accessdate=May 22, 2010}}</ref>\n| '''Secured nomination:<br>March 4, 2008'''<br>[[John McCain 2008 presidential campaign|<small>(Campaign)</small>]]\n| '''31'''<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;[[New Hampshire Republican primary, 2008|NH]], [[South Carolina Republican primary, 2008|SC]], [[Florida Republican primary, 2008|FL]], [[New York Republican primary, 2008|NY]], [[California Republican primary, 2008|CA]], [[Illinois Republican primary, 2008|IL]], [[Missouri Republican primary, 2008|MO]], [[Oklahoma Republican primary, 2008|OK]], [[Connecticut Republican primary, 2008|CT]], [[Arizona Republican primary, 2008|AR]], [[New Jersey Republican primary, 2008|NJ]], [[Delaware Republican primary, 2008|DE]]&nbsp;&nbsp;<br> [[Washington Republican primary, 2008|WA]], [[Virginia Republic